You are a debugging assistant. You will be presented with a failing test, and tools (functions) to access the source code of the system under test (SUT). Your task is to provide a step-by-step explanation of how the bug occurred, based on the failing test and the information you retrieved using tests about the SUT. You will be given 9 chances to interact with functions to gather relevant information. An example answer would look like follows.

Title: Diagnosis of test `testGenerateURLFragment`
Details: The test `testGenerateURLFragment` checks whether HTML entities such as `"` are correctly escaped to their corresponding character by the `StandardToolTipTagFragmentGenerator.generateToolTipFragment` method. However, the test failure indicates that this is not the case. Following the execution path, we find that `StandardToolTipTagFragmentGenerator.generateToolTipFragment` is not escaping any HTML code; instead, it is using its input `toolTipText` as is. Consequently, un-escaped strings are being returned, which leads to the error demonstrated by the test.

After providing this diagnosis, you will be prompted to suggest which methods would be the best locations to be fixed. The answers should be in the form of `ClassName.MethodName(ArgType1, ArgType2, ...)` without commentary (one per line), as your answer will be automatically processed before finally being presented to the user.

The test `['com.google.javascript.jscomp.CheckAccessControlsTest.testNoPrivateAccessForProperties6()']` failed.
The test looks like:

```java
399 :   public void testNoPrivateAccessForProperties6() {
400 :     // Overriding a private property with a non-private property
401 :     // in a different file causes problems.
402 :     test(new String[] { // error occurred here
403 :       "/** @constructor */ function Foo() {} " +
404 :       "/** @private */ Foo.prototype.bar_ = function() {};",
405 :       "/** @constructor \n * @extends {Foo} */ " +
406 :       "function SubFoo() {};" +
407 :       "SubFoo.prototype.bar_ = function() {};"
408 :     }, null, BAD_PRIVATE_PROPERTY_ACCESS);
409 :   }
```

The passing test with the highest token similarity to the failing test looks like:

 ```380 :   public void testNoPrivateAccessForProperties4() {
381 :     test(new String[] {
382 :       "/** @constructor */ function Foo() {} " +
383 :       "/** @private */ Foo.prototype.bar_ = function() {};",
384 :       "/** @constructor \n * @extends {Foo} */ " +
385 :       "function SubFoo() { this.bar_(); }"
386 :     }, null, BAD_PRIVATE_PROPERTY_ACCESS);
387 :   }
```

It failed with the following error message and call stack:

```
junit.framework.AssertionFailedError: Overriding private property of Foo.prototype.
 expected:<JSC_BAD_PRIVATE_PROPERTY_ACCESS: Access to private property {0} of {1} not allowed here.> but was:<JSC_PRIVATE_OVERRIDE: Overriding private property of {0}.>
	at com.google.javascript.jscomp.CompilerTestCase.test(CompilerTestCase.java:904)
	at com.google.javascript.jscomp.CompilerTestCase.test(CompilerTestCase.java:486)
	at com.google.javascript.jscomp.CompilerTestCase.test(CompilerTestCase.java:460)
	at com.google.javascript.jscomp.CompilerTestCase.test(CompilerTestCase.java:445)
	at com.google.javascript.jscomp.CheckAccessControlsTest.testNoPrivateAccessForProperties6(CheckAccessControlsTest.java:402)
```

The failing test `com.google.javascript.jscomp.CheckAccessControlsTest.testNoPrivateAccessForProperties6` belongs to the class `com.google.javascript.jscomp.CheckAccessControls`. The other class covered by failing tests is `com.google.javascript.jscomp.CheckAccessControls`.

Based on the available information, provide the signatures of the most likely culprit methods for the bug.
